f:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","TAO","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TAO represents Bittensor's native token, making it sensitive to AI narrative cycles and institutional adoption trends. The combination of TAO's volatility with Aevo's hourly funding intervals creates regular arbitrage windows, especially during periods of heightened AI sector speculation."}]]}]
10:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TAO/USDT funding rates on Aevo have shown strong correlation with broader AI token sentiment and Bittensor network developments. During Q4 2023 AI hype cycles, funding rates frequently exceeded 0.1% per hour as retail demand drove perpetual premiums. The hourly settlement mechanism amplifies these patterns, with rates often oscillating between positive and negative territory within 24-hour periods. Weekly funding costs can reach 10-30% annually during extreme market conditions, significantly higher than traditional crypto assets."}]]}]
11:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities on Aevo"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Aevo's unique position as both options and perpetuals provider creates cross-product arbitrage opportunities with TAO. Traders can exploit funding rate inefficiencies by hedging TAO perps against options positions or by arbitraging against spot holdings on centralized exchanges. The rollup architecture enables faster execution compared to mainnet DEXs, reducing slippage when capturing funding rate discrepancies. Pre-launch token markets on Aevo also provide early exposure to TAO-related projects, creating additional cross-asset arbitrage possibilities."}]]}]
12:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations for TAO Trading"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TAO's AI sector classification introduces specific risks including regulatory uncertainty around AI tokens and correlation with tech equity markets. Aevo's smaller liquidity pools compared to major CEXs can amplify slippage during volatile periods, particularly affecting larger arbitrage positions. The rollup's centralization aspects create smart contract and sequencer risks that traders must factor into their risk models. Additionally, Bittensor's validator economics can influence TAO supply dynamics, creating unexpected funding rate movements that purely technical arbitrage strategies may miss."}]]}]
13:["$","$L15",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Aevo's hourly funding differ from 8-hour cycles on other exchanges?","answer":"Aevo's hourly funding creates 8x more settlement opportunities compared to traditional 8-hour cycles, allowing for more granular arbitrage strategies. However, the underlying rate calculation still uses an 8-hour TWAP, so extreme short-term premiums are smoothed out over time."},{"question":"What makes TAO particularly suitable for funding rate arbitrage?","answer":"TAO's AI sector exposure creates sentiment-driven price movements that often disconnect perpetual futures from spot prices. The token's institutional adoption narrative and technical complexity also contribute to funding rate volatility as traders position for long-term trends."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage TAO funding rates between Aevo and centralized exchanges?","answer":"Yes, but consider Aevo's rollup withdrawal times and potential bridge delays when moving funds. The hourly funding on Aevo versus 8-hour cycles on CEXs creates timing arbitrage opportunities, but execution risk increases with cross-platform strategies."},{"question":"How do Aevo's trading fees affect TAO funding rate arbitrage profitability?","answer":"With 0.05% taker fees, frequent arbitrage trades can quickly erode profits from small funding rate differentials. The strategy works best when funding rate differences exceed 0.1% or when holding positions across multiple funding periods to amortize trading costs."}]}]
